g-Phe-NH2", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9974090456962585, "span": {"begin": 421, "end": 432}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3814"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "kisspeptin hormone", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.949934184551239, "span": {"begin": 485, "end": 503}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999420166015625, "span": {"begin": 545, "end": 553}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004967"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Estrogen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9936955571174622, "span": {"begin": 565, "end": 573}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:2099"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Estrogen Receptor Alpha", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9955592751502991, "span": {"begin": 565, "end": 588}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.48467347025871277, "span": {"begin": 608, "end": 615}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3814"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "kisspeptin hormone", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.972169041633606, "span": {"begin": 726, "end": 744}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:26284"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "ERa receptor", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9637334942817688, "span": {"begin": 766, "end": 778}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7004467248916626, "span": {"begin": 797, "end": 804}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3814"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Kisspeptin", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9961141347885132, "span": {"begin": 893, "end": 903}}], "text": "Kisspeptin (also known as metastin) is a key signalling neuropeptide hormone in mammals and some other vertebrates. &nbsp;The kisspeptin gene (KISS1) encodes a 145 amino acid prepolypeptide that is converted to 4 active peptides with names based on the number of amino acids (kisspeptin-54, 14, 13, 10); each active peptide is able to activate kisspeptin receptor (GPR54, KISS1R) because of a conserved c-terminal region Arg-Phe-NH2 group (Hu et al. 2018). &nbsp;Positive feedback for kisspeptin hormone production is due to increased levels of estrogen binding to Estrogen Receptor Alpha (ERa) receptors in neurons from the anteroventral periventricular nucleus (AVPV) region of the hypothalamus, while negative feedback for kisspeptin hormone production is due to ERa receptor activation of the neurons from the arcuate nucleus (ARC) region of the hypothalamus (Uenoyama et al. 2021). &nbsp;Kisspeptin signalling is important for prompting hormone production for coordinating the estrus cycle. &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:39:39 +0000 2026"}